In [[theoretical physics]], the hypothetical particle called the '''graviscalar''' or '''radion''' emerges as an excitation of general relativity's [[Metric tensor (general relativity)|metric tensor]], i.e. [[gravitational field]], but is indistinguishable from a [[scalar (physics)|scalar]] in four dimensions, as shown in [[Kaluza–Klein theory]]. The [[scalar field]] <math>\phi</math> comes from a component of the metric tensor <math>g_{55}</math> where the figure 5 labels an additional [[Five-dimensional space|fifth dimension]].  The only variations in the scalar field represent variations in the size of the extra dimension.  Also, in models with multiple extra dimensions, there exist several such particles.  Moreover, in theories with [[extended supersymmetry]], a graviscalar is usually a [[superpartner]] of the [[graviton]] that behaves as a particle with [[spin (physics)|spin]] 0.  This concept closely relates to the gauged [[Higgs mechanism|Higgs model]]s.

